{
  "text": "We first determined the population-specific optima of MHC class IIB allele numbers in wild-caught fish of lake (Gro\u00dfer Pl\u00f6ner See (GPS); n \u00bc 53 fish) and river (S\u00f6hrener Au (SAU); n \u00bc 49 fish) populations sampled in 2017. Consistent with previous work, we find that the MHC optimum is higher in lake (3.453 + 1.084, mean + s.e.) than in river (2.918 + 0.997, River2017-Lake2017, p \u00bc 0.011, t \u00bc 22.588, df \u00bc 100, twotailed t-test) fish. Remarkably, the population-specific MHC optima determined in 2010 (lake: 3.595 + + + + + 0.735, n \u00bc 42; river: 2.865 + 1.084, n \u00bc 37, River2010-Lake2010: p \u00bc 0.0007, t \u00bc 3.54, df \u00bc 77) do not differ significantly from those from 2017 (difference between River2017 and River2010: p \u00bc 0.85, t \u00bc 0.2351, df \u00bc 84; Lake2017-Lake2010: p \u00bc 0.47, t \u00bc 0.7266, df \u00bc 93), indicating immunogenetic stability of these two populations (figure 2a). Previous findings showed that the mean individual number of MHC alleles [CITATION_1] corresponds with the local optimum [CITATION_2] .",
